data.title: Tim Henman (Great Britain)
data.meta_description: The 30-year-old British serve-volleyer enjoyed the best season of his career in 2004 reaching the semi-finals of the French and U.S. Opens.
data.text:
ByEurosport

Published 04/11/2004 at 09:42 GMT

The 30-year-old serve-volleyer enjoyed the best season of his career in 2004 reaching the semi-finals of the French and U.S. Opens, plus a quarter-final outing at Wimbledon. While he was unable to win a title and defend his Paris Masters crown, the Briton has improved under coach Paul Annacone.

Born: 9 September 1974, Oxford

Residence: London, England

Professional Since: 1993

HOUSTON PROFILES

Roger Federer (Switzerland)

13/11/2004 at 06:48

Career Singles titles: 11

Singles Titles in 2004: None

MAJOR CHAMPIONSHIP RECORD 2004

Australian Open – 3R (lost to Guillermo Canas); Roland Garros – SF (lost to Guillermo Coria); Wimbledon – QF (lost to Mario Ancic); U.S. Open – SF (lost to Roger Federer)

BIOGRAPHY

With his first Masters Series victory in Paris last November, Tim Henman and Paul Annacone went on to forge a successful partnership in 2004.

The serve-volleyer's Australian Open campaign ended in the third round at the hands of Guillermo Canas, but Henman recovered to defeat Roger Federer on the way to the Rotterdam semi-finals the following month.

A final appearance in Indian Wells, losing to Federer has proven to be the 30-year-olds only final appearance this season.

However, at Roland Garros he became the first Briton since Mike Sangster in 1963 to play a semi-final match and reached the same stage at Flushing Meadow, three months later.

Croat Mario Ancic proved too good at Wimbledon, but Henman has had a consistent season and is sure to perform well in Houston, his first season-ending championship since 1999.
